What is Ractive.js

Ractive.js is a template driven UI library

Strongly influenced by {{ mustache }}

History

It was originally created at The Guardian theguardian.com to produce news applications.

  • Started in late 2013

  • One of the first VDOM libraries

  • Current version v1.3.4 (May 2019)

Author

Rich Harris

Github

Twitter

Graphics editor @ New York Times, Creator of Rollup, the module bundler used by the JavaScript ecosystem's most popular libraries.

Highlights

Unlike other frameworks, Ractive works for you, not the other way around.

  • Easy to learn

  • VDOM

  • Component based

  • Plays well with other libraries

  • No build step required

  • Good documentation

  • Batteries included

How to use

Just drop it in your page!

<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ractive"></script>
# npm
npm install --save-dev ractive

# Bower
bower install --save ractive

of course you can also

How does it look like

<div id="target"></div>

<script id="template" type="text/ractive">
  <p>{{greeting}}, {{name}}!</p>
</script>


var ractive = new Ractive({
  target: '#target',
  template: '#template',
  data: { greeting: 'Hello', name: 'world' },
  ...
})

Hello, world!

data object

What did that just do?

  • Created an Ractive instance that's bound to a div with an id of "target"

  • Read Mustache-style syntax from the special type text/ractive script tag.

  • Rendered the result as contents inside the div with an id of "target"

Reactive data

ractive.set('name', 'Devstaff');

Hello, World!

Data in the previous example is "reactive", if we change the data then the new value will appear on screen

<p>{{greeting}}, {{name}}!</p>

Hello, Devstaff!

Keypaths, get and set

var ractive = new Ractive({
  data: {
    foo: {
      bar: {
        baz: {
          faz: 'Devstaff rulez!'
        }
      }
    }
  },
  template: `
    {{ foo.bar.baz.faz }}
  `
})

A keypath is a kind of reference that represents the location of a piece of data.

Devstaff rulez!

Hello, Devstaff!

ractive.get('foo.bar.baz.faz');
ractive.set('foo.bar.baz.faz', 'Hello, Devstaff');

(Devstaff rules!)

Initialization Options

var ractive = new Ractive({
  data: {},        // The data for an instance, or default data for a component. 
  template: ``,    // The template to use (selector, string, function)
  target: '',      // ( or el: ) The element to render an instance to
  css: '',         // Scoped CSS for a component and its descendants
  use: [ ],        // An array of plugins to install on the instance
  components: { }, // A map of components available to the instance
  computed: { },   // A map of computed properties
  on: { },         // A hash of event listeners to subscribe
  oninit(){ },     // Lifecycle methods
  oncomplete(){ },
  onteardown(){ }
  ...
});

Some initialization options that we can pass to Ractive() and Ractive.extend()

Two-way data binding

Ractive({
  data: {
    msg: 'Hello World!'
  },
  template: `
    <input type="text" value="{{ msg }}"> {{ msg }}
  `
})

Two-way binding allows data to update bi-directionally, from data object to the UI and vice versa.

* Two-way data binding can be disabled via the twoway initialization option or the twoway input directive.

Expressions

Ractive({
  target: 'body',
  data: {
    price: 10,
    quantity: 5
  },
  template: `
    {{ price * quantity }}
  `
})

Expressions look just like regular mustaches.
Almost any valid JavaScript expression can be used inside mustaches

50

Live example - Expressions

Events

<button on-click="@global.alert( 'Activating!' )">Activate!</button>

Ractive.js, events are declarative.
We attach event handlers to DOM elements and components using on-* directives

<button on-click="@this.set( 'message', 'Hello' )">Change messsage</button>

Live example - Events

Methods

1. Inside the "on" instance object

Ractive({
  template: `
    <button type="button" on-click="pushme">Push me!</button>
    <button type="button" on-click="['consolemessage', 'Hello, World!']">Console message!</button>
    <button type="button" on-click="@this.instanceMethod('Hello, World!')">Instance method!</button>
  `,
  on: {
    pushme(context) {
      console.log('Hello, World!')
    },
    consolemessage(context, msg) {
      console.log(msg)
    }
  },
  instance(msg) {
    console.log(msg)
  }
})

2. Directly on instance level

Conditional sections

{{#if signedIn}}
  <!-- signed-in block -->
{{else}}
  <!-- not-signed-in block -->
{{/if}}

{{#if }} renders a block of markup if the reference is truthy or a non-empty iterable. {{else}} and {{elseif}} are supported and render if the previous condition failed.

Live example - Conditional sections

Iterative sections (aka loops)

{{#each people}}
  Hi! I'm {{.name}}!
{{else}}
  There's nobody here
{{/each}}

{{#each }} renders the block of markup for each item in the iterable.

...
people: [
  {name: 'Alice'},
  {name: 'Bob'},
  {name: 'Eve'}
]

Live example - Iterative sections

Partials

{{#partial item}}
  <li class="item">{{this}}!</li>
{{/partial}}

...

<ul>
  {{#each people}}
    {{> item }}
  {{/each}}
</ul>

Partials are reusable pieces of markup and a good way to split complex templates up into several more manageable chunks.

Live example - Partials

Components

Ractive.components.MyComponent = Ractive.extend({
  data: {
    message: ''    
  },
  template: `
    <input type="text" value="{{ message }}">
  `
})

const instance = Ractive({
  el: 'body',
  data: {
    text: ''
  },
  template: `
    <MyComponent message="{{ text }}" />
  `
})

Components are reusable blocks of code that can have both markup and functionality. They help to create a more modular and maintainable codebase.

Components Highlights

  • Components are "subclass" of the Ractive instance

  • Mappings are used to pass data from parent to child

  • Mappings are fed into a component through a custom attribute

  • Mappings can be dynamically bound to the parents data

  • Most of the normal Ractive initialization options also apply to components particularly the life cycle events

  • Leveraging Component files, Components can encapsulate markup, css and logic

Component files

Example component file

<!-- Define the markup for this component. -->
<h1>{{ title }}</h1>

<!-- Define the styles for this component. -->
<style>
  p { color: red; }
</style>

<!-- Define the behavior for this component. -->
<script>
component.exports = {
  onrender () {
    console.log('Component rendered');
  },
  data: {
    title: 'Hello World!'
  }
}
</script>

Live example - Components

Animations

var r = Ractive({
  el: '#main',
  template: '#tpl',
  data: {
    counter: 0
  }
})

setTimeout(() => {
  r.animate('counter', 20, { duration: 2000 })
}, 1000)

ractive.animate() will update the data and re-render any affected mustaches.

Live example - Animations

Transitions

<div fade-in>
  This div will fade into view
</div>

Normally, when an element is rendered, it just sort of gets plonked on the page. With Ractive you have more control using transition plugins.

Intro transition

<div fly-out>
